[
    {
        "content": "<p>James Dolan used to occasionally tell me about fun ways of thinking about <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/symmetric%20spaces\">[[symmetric spaces]]</a> and also <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/hermitian%20symmetric%20spaces\">[[hermitian symmetric spaces]]</a>.  I've given talks about <a href=\"https://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/tenfold/#symmetric\">the tenfold way and symmetric spaces</a>.  So I have a fondness for such topics.  But yesterday I started reading</p>\n<ul>\n<li>James Milne, <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Introduction%20to%20Shimura%20varieties\">[[Introduction to Shimura varieties]]</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>and I learned some basic stuff that's pretty fascinating.  </p>\n<p>First, a Shimura variety is a hermitian symmetric domain (where \"domain\" means it's isomorphic as a variety to an open subset of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>) modulo a discrete subgroup of isometries.</p>\n<p>Second, Shimura varieties are the right way to generalize <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/modular%20curves\">[[modular curves]]</a> to higher dimensions.  (That makes tons of sense if you notice that the hyperbolic plane is a hermitian symmetric domain, and a modular curve is the hyperbolic plane mod a discrete subgroup of isometries.)</p>\n<p>Third, we get automorphic representations from Shimura varieties, so they're important in the Langlands program.</p>",
        "id": 499528200,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1739465645
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And they point us up the chromatic levels:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/C_fPN0xzglFWcwVJI4xJaMtb/image.png\">image.png</a><br>\n<a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/topological+automorphic+form\">[[topological automorphic form]]</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/C_fPN0xzglFWcwVJI4xJaMtb/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"767x217\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/C_fPN0xzglFWcwVJI4xJaMtb/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 499551086,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1739471588
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Great!   </p>\n<p>By the way, when I said \"discrete subgroup of isometries\" I should have said \"arithmetic discrete subgroup of isometries\" - we need to stay in the world of algebraic (or arithmetic?) geometry.</p>",
        "id": 499575394,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1739477824
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am <a href=\"https://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/octonions/integers/\">extremely fond</a> of quotients of <em>real</em> hyperbolic space by discrete subgroups - like the quotient of 9-dimensional hyperbolic space by the discrete group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>PSL</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">O</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{PSL}(2,\\mathbf{O})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">PSL</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">O</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{O}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">O</span></span></span></span> is the Cayley integral octonions, forming a copy of the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mtext>E</mtext><mn>8</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{E}_8</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">E</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">8</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> lattice in the octonions.</p>",
        "id": 499575989,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1739478025
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>However I think there are some similar juicy examples connected to <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_hyperbolic_space\">complex hyperbolic space</a>, and these are likely to be Shimura varieties.   </p>\n<p>(I gravitate toward concrete examples - especially 'exotic' examples connected to the octonions, since there's a tiny chance I can find something new there, that the experts in 'unexotic' algebraic geometry might not have already found.)</p>",
        "id": 499576519,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1739478218
    }
]